This is a Python web scraping and R data analysis project. Its objective is to identify molecular structures within 
traditional Chinese medicine formulas capable of treating hypercholesterolemia that can bind to chemical molecules within the bile acid family.

Using web scraping techniques, I obtained the molecular structures for each drug from the TCMID/TCMBank/TCMSP databases, as detailed in File 10.

Through the TCMSP database, I batch-crawled mol files containing the structure and related information for each molecule, as detailed in Files 1, 7, 8, and 9.

The mol files were batch-converted into SMILES strings (a standardized format using ASCII characters to explicitly describe molecular structures), as detailed in File 2.

SMILES codes were used to batch-fetch ADMET data (Absorption, Distribution, Metabolism, Excretion, Toxicity) from the ADMETlab website via web scraping, as detailed in File 3.

I performed batch visualization of the obtained ADMET data using R programming, as detailed in File 4.

SMILES codes are also used to generate molecular fingerprints. See File 5 for details.

Molecular fingerprints enable calculation of Tanimoto coefficients for similarity comparisons with chemical molecules in the bile acid family. See File 6 for details.

All code was written by myself. I extend my gratitude to my advisor, Professor Wang Chao, for his guidance and support.
